entry.title: iwa: Make sure that IWA installation from CLI is working on ChromeOS
entry.content:
Our intention was that `MaybeInstallIwaFromCommandLine` is called on

browser startup. However, the browser's complex startup behavior in

conjunction with the many different ways it is started on ChromeOS (Ash

vs. Lacros, first run vs. not first run, etc.) made it so that

`MaybeInstallIwaFromCommandLine` is not called consistently. Instead of

trying to catch all the different startup behaviors of the browser on

ChromeOS, I instead moved the installation logic into

`IsolatedWebAppCommandLineInstallManager::Start` for ChromeOS.



This is something that should be revisited once we have proper developer

UI to install IWAs, and once Lacros becomes the default.

entry.title: [Auto-disable Accessibility] Update AccessibilityState system observers and init timeline
entry.content:
This CL continues the AccessibilityState refactoring/improvements as

part of the auto-disable accessibility feature.



This CL updates the AccessibilityState class to register as a listener

of the ActivityState in ApplicationStatus. A user can change the

enabled/disabled accessibility services while Chrome is in the

background, so when an Activity is resumed, AccessibilityState should

query the services again. We also add an unregister method when

all Activities have been destroyed.



We also move the ContentObserver registration out of the

browser_accessibility_state_impl_android, and into the Java-side

init process methods. The AccessibilityState observations should

not be tied to the web contents, and should exist even when there is

no webContents or tab so the UI can use the same state machine.

During postNativeInit we register the system observers, and in

startup add a deferred task to query the state so that it can

be ready for clients asap.



We also move the collection of AccessibilityServiceInfo histograms

into the AccessibilityState init process, and any time the system

settings change. This is cleaner than the current method which

records the stats anytime a new webContents object is created,

since such stats are not inherently tied to webContents.



We add some asserts to ensure that AccessibilityState system

observer registration happens before any client queries of state.

entry.title: Revert "[Extensions] Change install directory of .zip file installs."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 1a7cebd3b866379d8955857853102192199c2fc4.



Reason for revert: This causes unexpected .zip file deletion due to incorrect extension_garbage_collector.cc logic. See https://crbug.com/1378775#c12 for details.



Original change's description:

> [Extensions] Change install directory of .zip file installs.

>

> Change the install directory to "UnpackedExtensions" subdir of the

> profile directory.

>

> I've put it behind a default enabled flag to give us the later option of

> an emergency rollback due to the complexity of the change and the fact

> that the change modifies files.

>

> Before this change we installed .zip file installed extensions to a

> unique subdir of base::DIR_TEMP. This could cause confusion when the

> temporary directory used for installation would be deleted by the OS

> (e.g. /tmp on Linux, `NSTemporaryDirectory` on Mac, and etc.) which are

> commonly cleared on varied timelines). This caused issues like the html

> file for a badge popup failing to be found at runtime and the extension

> disappearing from chromium on restart when it no longer could find the

> directory.

>

> After this change we install them to a non-temporary

> "UnpackedExtensions" subdir of the profile dir (at the same level as the

> "Extensions" dir where we install packed .crx and webstore installs).

>

> This allows the extension to persist until the user chooses to uninstall

> the (from .zip) extension.

>

> I kept the original install folder format of (example good.zip)

> ..//UnpackedExtensions/good_XXXXXX/ where the Xs are a

> unique combination (for that folder) of alphanumeric characters but that

> was to be consistent more than anything else.

>

> Extra work had to be done with extension_garbage_collector.cc to ensure

> that if the directory deletion failed it would eventually come around

> and delete/cleanup the directory so it doesn't linger (because there

> is now a new install location).

>

> This does not cause the Extension to be synced.

>

> Low-Coverage-Reason: extension_garbage_collector.cc we don't seem to

> cover NOTREACHED() in unit tests.

>

This is a reland of crrev.com/c/4418953, which was reverted due to

causing crashes (crbug.com/1436044). The issue was SetTimeBeforeDiscard

memory saver flag was on, HighEfficiencyModePolicy is not created and

so the check fails. The HighEfficiencyModePolicy is not needed when the

flag is on, so the fix is just to check that the flag is off before

CL also introduces a command line switch that the UPTM reads to set the

default value of the pref. Once the multistate memory saver is rolled

out, the user will be able to control the pref from the settings page,

and this command line switch will no longer be needed.

entry.title: Optimize 2D Canvas style setters
entry.content:
This CL eliminates unnecessary conditional branches, switch statements

and function call overhead when setting the fillStyle and strokeStyle

attributes of CanvasRenderingContext2D.



This change also updates the 2d.gradient.object.update.html tests to

make them more robust. Before this change, blink was not spec

compliant and the existing test did not catch it. The problem

was that because blink was deferring the evaluation of the

CanvasGradient until the time of first draw, it was catching changes

to the CanvasGradient that were made after setting fillStyle. So the

test was not robust enough to truly verify that the CanvasGradient

object is live. The test now modifies the CanvasGradient between

consecutive draws, which is the test that the old implementation would

have failed because the gradient would have been baked-in after the

first draw.



This change improves MotionMark Canvas Lines by 0.4% on M1 MacOS

entry.title: iwa: Add IsolatedWebAppCommandLineInstallManager for CLI installation
entry.content:
There are two command line switches to install an IWA for development

purposes: `--install-isolated-web-app-from-url` and `...-from-file`.



`MaybeInstallAppFromCommandLine` parsed these switches, and, if present,

installed an IWA based on these switches.



This CL refactors the function to instead forward the installation

request to a newly introduced `IsolatedWebAppCommandLineInstallManager`.

`MaybeInstallAppFromCommandLine` used blocking file I/O on the UI thread

(`base::MakeAbsoluteFilePath`, `base::PathExists`, and

`base::DirectoryExists`). The refactored code instead runs these

functions on a separate thread that allows blocking. The new code also

creates `Scoped(Profile)KeepAlive`s so that browser and profile are kept

alive during installation.



Now that the `IsolatedWebAppCommandLineInstallManager` is owned by the

`WebAppProvider`, we also no longer need to worry about profile

shutdowns, since the `WebAppProvider` and hence the

`IsolatedWebAppCommandLineInstallManager` will be deleted before the

profile shuts down.



Low-Coverage-Reason: Debug logging code in profile_keep_alive_types and

keep_alive_types has low coverage, which seems

fine for that code and also matches existing

coverage in these files.

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2/test: Update H.264 CAPTURE queue buffer refresh
entry.content:
The H.264 decoder was previously setup to refresh CAPTURE queue buffers

based on which buffers had a different buffer ID than the current buffer

(as to not override the current data). This becomes an issues especially

if a picture is a long term reference and it's data gets lost.



This change updates DPB to indicate the CAPTURE queue indices of its

pictures which have not yet been output. The

GetReusuableReferenceSlots() function is updated as well to prevent

refreshing buffers which have a DPB element not yet output attached to

them.



This change results in all h264_baseline and h264_main bitstreams

passing their tests.

entry.title: Introduce SyncPrefs::Set[Os]TypeDisabledByPolicy
entry.content:
Currently, Sync's per-datatype prefs are exposed via

SyncPrefs::GetPrefNameFor[Os]Type(). This is mostly used for

enterprise policies that want to force-disable some types.

We want to make the pref names private, to avoid layering violations

and bugs (see linked bug).

To do that, this CL introduces new static helpers

SyncPrefs::Set[Os]TypeDisabledByPolicy(), which set a given type to

disabled in a passed-in PrefValueMap, and updates policy handlers to

use that instead of setting the prefs manually.

entry.title: [omnibox] Makes OmniboxController own OmniboxEditModel
entry.content:
Currently OmniboxEditModel - owned by OmniboxView - is at the center of

the omnibox UI machinery. It owns an instance of OmniboxController

and OmniboxClient, while OmniboxController owns AutocompleteController.



A better long-term direction is for the OmniboxController to be at the

center of both the Autocomplete and the omnibox UI machinery and own

both OmniboxClient and OmniboxEditModel in addition to the

AutocompleteController.



This change does the following:

- transfers ownership of OmniboxClient to OmniboxController.

- reverses ownership model of OmniboxController and OmniboxEditModel.

- makes OmniboxView own OmniboxController instead of OmniboxEditModel.



Given that the lifetime of all these objects is ultimately bound to

that of the OmniboxView, this change in ownership should be safe.

entry.title: Disable updatable maps in the `Libunwindstack` unwinder.
entry.content:
Updatable maps do not appear to make any positive different to

unwinding based on local testing, and we have not verified

whether they help unwinding materially during Chrome tracing.



Disabling updatable maps should (hopefully) fix crashes

(attached bug) and removed the need for additional

complexity to handle them in `ModuleCache`. No other Chrome

unwinders currently use updatable maps.



We already have trace events when unwinding fails due to a

`MAP_ERROR`, and we can use that event to study whether

we really need updatable maps in the future.

entry.title: [DownloadBubble] Call OpenDownload when main row view button is pressed
entry.content:
The main button on the DownloadBubbleRowView was previously executing

the OPEN_WHEN_COMPLETE command, which is not implemented for offline

items. This was causing nothing to happen in the UI when an offline

item's row was clicked on. This CL switches this to directly call

OpenDownload() on the model, which opens the download or marks it as

open-when-complete, and for offline items launches the page it was

downloaded from.
